  "sections": {
    "Overview": {
      "text": "Two most common devices are the C-MAC and the Glidescope\n[1]\nBoth CMAC and Glidescope systems offer both hyperangulated and standard geometry blades\nIncreasingly utilized in emergency airway management\n[2]",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
    "Indications": {
      "text": "Any patient requiring\nintubation\nParticularly useful in patients with known or anticipated\ndifficult intubation",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": [
        {
          "text": "intubation",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Intubation"
        },
        {
          "text": "difficult intubation",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Predicting_the_difficult_airway"
        }
      ]
    },
    "Contraindications": {
      "text": "No absolute contraindications\nRelative:\nBlood or emesis in airway\nForeign body removal",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
    "Equipment_Needed": {
      "text": "Video laryngoscope\nRigid stylet if hyperangulated blade is used\nAll other equipment necessary for\nendotracheal intubation",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": [
        {
          "text": "endotracheal intubation",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Intubation"
        }
      ]
    },
    "Procedure": {
      "text": "Hyperangulated video laryngoscope\nPatient ideally in neutral spine position (as opposed to \"sniffing\" position for direct laryngoscopy)\nAfter induction, use right hand to \"scissor\" mouth open\nPlace hyperangulated blade midline and slowly advance with progressive identification of airway landmarks\nAdvance blade into vallecula\nWhen cords fill entire screen (Cormack-Lehane Grade I), slightly retract laryngoscopy so that cords only occupy upper 1/3 of screen (CL Grade II, allows for passage of ETT with rigid stylet)\n[3]\nIf intubation is attempted with the best view possible, operators often have difficulty advancing the tube around the tongue and hypopharyngeal soft tissues\nStandard geometry video laryngoscope\nSame technique utilized with\ndirect laryngoscopy\nCan either visualize directly or utilize video screen for tube delivery",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": [
        {
          "text": "direct laryngoscopy",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Direct_laryngoscopy"
        }
      ]
    },
    "Complications": {
      "text": "Risk of equipment failure with hyperangulated laryngoscope (unable to obtain direct view if screen fails)\nRisk of camera contamination with blood or emesis in airway\nForeign body removal with hyperangulated laryngoscope less successful than with Macintosh laryngoscope\n[4]",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
